# Avatar Provider Implementation Guide

## Provider Base Class

All avatar providers must extend [Provider.js](mdc:src/providers/Provider.js) and implement the `getUrl()` method.

## Provider Structure

```javascript
import Author from "../src/Author.js";
import Provider, { Scope } from "./Provider.js";

export default class YourProvider extends Provider {
  constructor() {
    // Specify scope: Scope.DOMAIN or Scope.EMAIL
    super("providername", Scope.DOMAIN);
  }

  /**
   * Gets the profile picture URL for the given author.
   * @param {Author} author - The author to get the URL for.
   * @returns {Promise<string>} The profile picture URL.
   */
  async getUrl(author) {
    // Implementation
  }
}
```

## Provider Scopes

### Scope.DOMAIN

Use for providers that work with domain names (company logos):

- Google (favicon for domain)
- IconHorse
- FaviconWebpage
- Splitbee

```javascript
constructor() {
  super("google", Scope.DOMAIN);
}

async getUrl(author) {
  const domain = author.getDomain();
  return `https://www.google.com/s2/favicons?domain=${domain}&sz=128`;
}
```

### Scope.EMAIL

Use for providers that work with email addresses (personal avatars):

- Gravatar
- Libravatar
- DuckDuckGo

```javascript
constructor() {
  super("gravatar", Scope.EMAIL);
}

async getUrl(author) {
  const email = author.getAuthor();
  // Hash email and build URL
  return gravatarUrl;
}
```

## URL Construction

### Query Parameters

Use clear query parameter construction:

```javascript
const params = new URLSearchParams({
  domain: author.getDomain(),
  size: 128,
});
return `https://api.example.com/avatar?${params}`;
```

### Hash Generation

For providers requiring email hashes (like Gravatar):

```javascript
// Use MD5 or SHA256 as required by provider
const emailHash = await this.hashEmail(author.getAuthor());
return `https://gravatar.com/avatar/${emailHash}`;
```

## Error Handling

Providers should handle errors gracefully:

```javascript
async getUrl(author) {
  try {
    const url = await this.fetchAvatarUrl(author);
    return url;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(`Error fetching from ${this.name}:`, error);
    return null;  // Return null on failure
  }
}
```

## Network Requests

When making HTTP requests:

- Use `fetch()` API
- Set appropriate headers
- Handle network failures
- Respect rate limits

```javascript
async getUrl(author) {
  try {
    const response = await fetch(url, {
      method: 'GET',
      headers: {
        'User-Agent': 'Thunderbird-Auto-Profile-Picture'
      }
    });

    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}`);
    }

    return response.url;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(`${this.name} request failed:`, error);
    return null;
  }
}
```

## Special Provider Types

### BIMI Provider

BIMI requires DNS lookups and certificate validation:

- Check for BIMI DNS records
- Validate SVG signatures
- Return verified brand logos only

### Fallback Providers

Some providers serve as fallbacks:

- Should be reliable and fast
- Should have high success rate
- Example: DuckDuckGo, IconHorse

## Provider Registration

Add new providers to [ProviderFactory.js](mdc:src/providers/ProviderFactory.js):

```javascript
import YourProvider from "./YourProvider.js";

static getProviders() {
  return [
    new GravatarProvider(),
    new GoogleProvider(),
    new YourProvider(),  // Add here
    // ...
  ];
}
```

## Testing Providers

Test providers with various inputs:

- Valid emails
- Emails without avatars
- Invalid domains
- Network failures
- Rate limit scenarios

```javascript
// Example test cases
const author1 = await Author.fromAuthor("user@example.com");
const author2 = await Author.fromAuthor("invalid@nonexistent.xyz");
const url1 = await provider.getUrl(author1);
const url2 = await provider.getUrl(author2); // Should handle gracefully
```

## Performance Guidelines

- Cache DNS lookups when applicable
- Minimize network requests
- Return quickly on failure (don't retry multiple times)
- Use HTTP/2 when available
- Respect provider rate limits

## Privacy Considerations

- Don't log email addresses in production
- Use secure HTTPS connections only
- Consider user privacy settings
- Document what data is sent to provider

```javascript
// Good - log domain only
console.log(`Fetching avatar for domain: ${author.getDomain()}`);

// Bad - logs email address
console.log(`Fetching avatar for: ${author.getAuthor()}`);
```
